Lab 8: Transformations

2020-11-04

  • Simple case: Transforming \(X\) with only one predictor
  • General strategy with multiple regressors.
  • Transformations of Nonpositive Variables

Sometimes, our data will not follow a linear relationship on the original scale, but an (approximate) linear relationship can be induced through a transformation.

First: two rules of thumb. Log rule. If values range over more than one order of magnitude, a log transformation can often be helpful (consider how this can affect leverage).

Range rule. If the range of a variable is considerably less than one order of magnitude, tranformations may not be helpful.

This is a good starting point to set our expectations, but we need more systematic ways to choose transformations.

Simple case: Transforming \(X\) with only one predictor

For simple regression with a single predictor, we may use invTranPlot in the car package (Companion to Applied Regression) to determine a proper transformation. Our goal is to make the mean function linear after some transformation \(\Psi_S(X,\lambda)\): \[ E(Y\mid X) \approx \beta_0 + \beta_1\Psi_S(X,\lambda). \] This can be easily done because we only have one \(X\).

library(alr4)
library(car)

data(Auto)
# subset to continuous, positive predictors of mpg
Auto <- Auto %>% select(mpg,displacement,horsepower,weight,acceleration)

# look at the pairs plot
pairs(Auto)

None of these variables violate the range rule, but we do see some non-linearities in their relationships with our response mpg.

invTranPlot

Suppose we are interested in predicting mpg with only horsepower.

invTranPlot will produce a scatter plot of the chosen variables and plot the least squares line for different choices of \(\lambda\) in the scaled power transformation: \[ \Psi_{S}(X,\lambda) = \frac{X^{\lambda}-1}{\lambda}.\]

Note that \[ \lim_{\lambda \rightarrow 0} \frac{X^{\lambda}-1}{\lambda} = \log(X). \] Typically \(\lambda \in [-2,2]\).

# basic syntax is invTranPlot(y~x,data=data)
# NOTE this will produce a plot and a data frame

itp <- invTranPlot(mpg~horsepower,data=Auto)

itp
##       lambda      RSS
## 1 -0.4852651 7701.809
## 2 -1.0000000 7929.141
## 3  0.0000000 7899.932
## 4  1.0000000 9385.916
# invTranPlot only works for a single predictor - it will throw an error if you try and use more than one.

From this data we might choose \(\hat{\lambda} = -0.5\), and fit a regression of the response mpg on 1/sqrt(horsepower). The choice of lambda does not need to perfect, and choosing \(\hat{\lambda}=0\) (log(horsepower)) here would also be fine.

General strategy with multiple regressors.

The case becomes more complicated with multiple regressors. We aim to find a suitably transformed \(\tilde{X}\) and \(\tilde{Y}\) with \[ E(\tilde{Y}\mid \tilde{X}) \approx \beta_0 + \beta_1\tilde{X}_1+\ldots+\beta_p\tilde{X}_p. \] First, we may have to apply Box-Cox transformation for all predictors, to make them close to normal distribution. Then we find a proper transformation for response \(Y\). The first step is necessary for a better result.

Box-Cox transformation

The Box-Cox transformation is a generalization of power transformation. We choose to standardize it by a factor of geometric mean for stability. For a generic variable \(U\), \[ \Psi_{M}(U,\lambda) = \begin{cases} gm(U)^{1-\lambda}\times \frac{U^\lambda - 1}{\lambda},&\lambda \neq 0,\\ gm(U)\times \log(U), & \lambda = 0, \end{cases} \] where \(gm(U)\) is the geometric mean \[ gm(U) = \exp\left( \sum_{i=1}^n \log U_i / n\right) = \left(\prod_{i=1}^n U_i\right)^{1/n}. \]

Step 1: Transforming all the predictor simultaneously

  • The Box-Cox transformation can be applied to mutiple predictors simultaneously.
  • The purpose is to make the transformed predictors \(\psi(X)\) close to normal, or at least approximately linearly correlated.
  • This is a preparation for the next step: Finding a good transforming the response \(Y\).
  • Basic syntax is powerTransform(cbind(x1,x2,,xp)~1,data=data)

We look at the highway example, we eliminate slim as a variable to be transformed because its range is too narrow. We also make the sigs variable positive by adding a constant. For the remaining predictors, we get the summary of transformations using the multivariate BoxCox method.

Highway$sigs1 <- with(Highway, (sigs * len + 1)/len)
summary(powerTransform(cbind(len, adt, trks, shld, sigs1) ~ 1, Highway))
Highway_tr = Highway
Highway_tr[,c('len','adt','trks','sigs1')] = bcPower(Highway[,c('len','adt','trks','sigs1')],rep(0,4))
plot(Highway_tr[,c('rate','len','adt','trks','sigs1')])
  • The summary table gives the value of \(\widehat{\lambda}\) in the column marked Est. power.
  • The estimated powers for len, adt, trks, and sigs1 are close to 0, and the power for shld does not appear to be different from 1.
  • The test that all powers are 0 is firmly rejected, as well as the test for no transformation at all.
  • Since \({\lambda} = (0,0,0,1,0)\) is in the corresponding confidence intervals, we choose these values for interpretability.
  • The predictors in transformed scale shows a linear mean function, or at least approximately so.
## bcPower Transformations to Multinormality 
##       Est.Power Std.Err. Wald Lower Bound Wald Upper Bound
## len      0.1437   0.2127          -0.2732           0.5607
## adt      0.0509   0.1206          -0.1854           0.2872
## trks    -0.7028   0.6177          -1.9134           0.5078
## shld     1.3456   0.3630           0.6341           2.0570
## sigs1   -0.2408   0.1496          -0.5341           0.0525
##

## LR test, lambda = (0 0 0 0 0)  23.324467  5 0.0002926014
## LR test, lambda = (1 1 1 1 1) 132.857421  5 0.0000000000
## LR test, lambda = (0 0 0 1 0)   6.088599  5 0.2976930877

Step 2: Transforming the response

Once the predictors are transformed, we can turn our attention to transforming the response.

To this end, we aim to find a \(\lambda_y\) such that we have an approximately linear relationship: \[E(\widehat{Y}|Y) \approx \alpha_0 + \alpha_1 \Psi_S(Y,\lambda_y)\] where \(\hat{Y}\) are the fitted values from the regression of the untransformed \(Y\) on the appropriately transformed regressors \(X\). This implies examining a graph with \(\hat{Y}\) on the vertical axis and \(Y\) on the horizontal axis, called an inverse fitted value plot. If the plot shows a clear non-linear trend, some transformation on \(Y\) would be necessary. The parameter \(\lambda_y\) can be selected either to minimize the \(RSS\) or visually.

Inverse response plot

#Highway$sigs1 = (Highway$sigs*Highway$len+1)/Highway$len

m2 <- lm(rate ~ log(len) + log(adt) + log(trks) + shld + log(sigs1) + slim, Highway)

inverseResponsePlot(m2)

##       lambda      RSS
## 1  0.1846179 30.62130
## 2 -1.0000000 34.71600
## 3  0.0000000 30.72613
## 4  1.0000000 32.45792

As with the inverse transformation plot, the values of \(RSS\) for the displayed curves are shown in the text window. In the example the value of \(\hat{\lambda}=0.18\) minimizes \(RSS\), but there is little to distinguish using this value of \(\lambda\) from the simpler case of \(\lambda=0\), meaning that the fitted curves for these two values of \(\lambda\) match the data nearly equally well. The log-transform is therefore suggested.

Box-Cox

An alternative to the above is the Box-Cox transformation, this time applied on \(Y\). The purpose is make the transformed data close to normal distribution.

boxCox(m2)

We find \(\widehat{\lambda}\) that maximizes the likelihood as the above plot shows. We see that \(0\) is in the interval again. So the Box-Cox approach also endorses the log transform.

We can get the numerical summary of the plot by

summary(powerTransform(m2))
## bcPower Transformation to Normality 
##    Est.Power Std.Err. Wald Lower Bound Wald Upper Bound
## Y1   -0.2384   0.2891           -0.805           0.3282
## 
## Likelihood ratio tests about transformation parameters
##                              LRT df         pval
## LR test, lambda = (0)  0.6884455  1 4.066936e-01
## LR test, lambda = (1) 18.2451001  1 1.942249e-05

Transformations of Nonpositive Variables

  1. Consider transformations of the form \((U+\gamma)^{\lambda}\), where \(\gamma\) is sufficiently large to ensure that \(U+\gamma\) is strictly positive.

  2. Yeo and Johnson (2000) proposed a family of transformations that can be used without restrictions on \(U\) that have many of the good properties of the Box Cox power family: \[ \Psi_{YJ}(U,\lambda)= \left\{ \begin{array}{ll} \Psi_S(U+1,\lambda), & U \geq 0\\ -\Psi_S(-U+1,2-\lambda) & U<0 \\ \end{array} \right. \]
